  <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
    <p>
      For most construction firm owners, the "Bidding Bottleneck" is the silent killer of scale. You reach a point where you simply can't bid more work without hiring another estimator or outsourcing to a consultant. Both options feel like a compromise. You're either adding heavy fixed overhead or paying a premium for someone else to own your most critical business logic.
    </p>
    <p>
      The reality of modern pre-construction is that the "math" shouldn't be the bottleneck. If your estimating process relies on the tribal knowledge of a single expert or the fragile links of a legacy Excel file, you don't have a system. You have a person-dependent risk.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-[#2D2442] mt-10 mb-6">The Consultant Trap: The Illusion of Easy Capacity</h2>
    
    <figure class="my-10">
      <img src="https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1772442198624-4fc4d7281e89?crop=entropy&cs=tinysrgb&fit=max&fm=jpg&ixid=M3w4NTU2MDF8MHwxfHNlYXJjaHwxfHxjb25zdHJ1Y3Rpb24lMjBibHVlcHJpbnRzfGVufDB8fHx8MTc3NDk4NzgyM3ww&ixlib=rb-4.1.0&q=80&w=1080" alt="Construction professional reviewing blueprints at a project site" class="rounded-xl shadow-lg w-full h-96 object-cover">
      <figcaption class="text-sm text-gray-500 mt-3 text-center italic">
        Photo by <a href="https://unsplash.com/@gnhearingglobal?utm_source=leonardo_rails_app&utm_medium=referral" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="hover:text-blue-600 underline decoration-dotted transition-colors">GN Group</a> on <a href="https://unsplash.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="hover:text-blue-600 underline decoration-dotted transition-colors">Unsplash</a>
      </figcaption>
    </figure>

    <p>
      Hiring construction estimating consultants feels like a quick win. You get "expert" eyes on your takeoffs without the burden of a full-time salary. But this convenience comes with a heavy, often hidden price tag:
    </p>
    <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
      <li><strong>Knowledge Leakage:</strong> Every time a consultant finishes a bid, they take the "how" and "why" of those numbers with them. Your company learns nothing.</li>
      <li><strong>The Per-Bid Tax:</strong> Your cost to acquire new work stays high. You're renting expertise, not building a permanent asset that lowers your cost over time.</li>
      <li><strong>Lack of Agility:</strong> If a client asks for a quick revision or a "what-if" scenario, you're back on the consultant's clock, waiting for their availability.</li>
    </ul>

